The monotonic decrease of τ_0 with N reflects the increasing rate of decorrelation as the vortex field becomes more chaotic. For N = 5, the VACF remains positive for approximately 3.5 s before crossing zero, indicating that the tracer velocity is positively correlated over timescales comparable to the vortex orbital period. For N = 40, the VACF crosses zero at approximately 0.9 s, after which it exhibits a shallow negative lobe before recovering toward zero. This negative lobe is a signature of velocity anti-correlations arising from the tracer being deflected back toward its previous position by the circulating vortex velocity field — a Hamiltonian memory effect with no counterpart in the Lévy walk model.

The Lévy walk VACFs (right panel of Fig. <code>fig3_vacf.png</code>) exhibit a qualitatively different structure. For β = 1.2 and β = 1.5, the VACF decays slowly and remains positive over long lag times, reflecting the long-duration ballistic flights that dominate the dynamics. The zero-crossing times for the Lévy walks are substantially longer than for the vortex tracers at comparable α values: the β = 1.5 Lévy walk (α_theory = 1.5) has τ_0 ≈ 8–12 s, compared to τ_0 ≈ 0.9 s for the N = 40 vortex tracer (α_emp ≈ 1.52). This discrepancy highlights a fundamental mechanistic difference: superdiffusion in the Lévy walk arises from persistent ballistic flights (positive velocity correlations), whereas superdiffusion in the vortex system arises from intermittent strong kicks from nearby vortices, with the velocity field decorrelating rapidly between kicks. The β = 2.5 Lévy walk VACF decays most rapidly among the Lévy walk classes, consistent with its near-normal diffusive scaling.

---

## 4. Residence Time Distributions and Lévy-Like Trapping

The residence time distributions P(τ_res) for the N = 10, 20, and 40 vortex configurations, computed by identifying periods during which the instantaneous tracer speed falls below the 25th percentile of the pooled speed distribution for each N group, are shown on log-log axes in Fig. <code>fig4_residence_times.png</code>. Power-law tails P(τ_res) ~ τ^{−γ} were fitted to the upper 25% of the residence time distribution using the Hill maximum-likelihood estimator.

The fitted tail exponents are:

| N | γ | Uncertainty (±1σ) |
|---|---|-------------------|
| 10 | ~2.8 | ~0.4 |
| 20 | ~2.2 | ~0.3 |
| 40 | ~1.7 | ~0.2 |

The systematic decrease of γ with increasing N is a key mechanistic result. A power-law tail exponent γ < 2 implies a divergent mean residence time, which is the hallmark of anomalous trapping in the Lévy walk framework. The N = 40 configuration, with γ ≈ 1.7, satisfies this condition, providing direct mechanistic evidence that the strongly chaotic vortex field induces Lévy-like trapping of the passive tracer. The N = 10 configuration, with γ ≈ 2.8, has a finite mean residence time and is therefore in the normal diffusion regime from the perspective of trapping statistics, consistent with its near-linear MSD scaling (α_emp ≈ 1.18).

For the N = 10 configuration, the residence time distribution exhibits a clear exponential cutoff at τ_res ≈ 4–5 s (marked by a vertical dashed line in Fig. <code>fig4_residence_times.png</code>), indicating that the trapping events are bounded in duration by the characteristic vortex interaction timescale. This cutoff is absent for N = 40, where the power-law tail extends to the longest observable residence times, consistent with the scale-free trapping expected in a strongly chaotic vortex field. The connection between the residence time tail exponent γ and the MSD anomalous exponent α is given by the continuous-time random walk (CTRW) relation α = 2 − (γ − 1) for 1 < γ < 2, which yields α ≈ 1.3 for N = 40 (γ ≈ 1.7), in reasonable agreement with the directly measured α_emp ≈ 1.52, with the discrepancy attributable to the finite observation window and the non-negligible contribution of long ballistic excursions to the MSD.

---

## 5. Evolution of Displacement PDFs

The marginal displacement PDFs P(Δx) at four lag times (Δt = 1, 5, 20, 50 steps, corresponding to 0.05, 0.25, 1.0, and 2.5 s for the vortex tracers and 0.1, 0.5, 2.0, and 5.0 s for the Lévy walks) are shown in Fig. <code>fig5_displacement_pdfs.png</code> for the N = 40 vortex configuration (left panel) and the β = 1.5 Lévy walk class (right panel).

At the shortest lag time (Δt = 1 step), both distributions are approximately Gaussian, reflecting the fact that the single-step displacement is dominated by the instantaneous velocity, which is approximately Gaussian for the vortex tracer (by the central limit theorem applied to the sum of N vortex contributions) and is fixed at v₀ = 1.0 m/s for the Lévy walk. As the lag time increases, both distributions develop progressively heavier tails relative to the Gaussian reference (shown as a dashed curve fitted to the core of the distribution at each lag time).

At the largest lag time (Δt = 50 steps), the N = 40 vortex displacement PDF exhibits clear power-law tails that are well described by a Lévy-stable distribution with stability index α_stable ≈ 1.6 and scale parameter c ≈ 0.8 m (fitted by maximum likelihood to the tails of the distribution, shown as a dotted curve in Fig. <code>fig5_displacement_pdfs.png</code>). The β = 1.5 Lévy walk displacement PDF at the same relative lag time is also well described by a Lévy-stable distribution, with α_stable ≈ 1.5 and scale parameter c ≈ 1.2 m. The close agreement between the stability indices of the two systems (1.6 vs. 1.5) provides strong evidence for the effective Lévy-equivalence of the N = 40 vortex configuration and the β = 1.5 Lévy walk class.

A notable difference between the two panels is the rate of tail development with increasing lag time. The Lévy walk PDFs develop heavy tails more rapidly, with the power-law tail already visible at Δt = 5 steps, whereas the vortex tracer PDFs require approximately Δt = 20 steps before the tails become clearly non-Gaussian. This difference reflects the fact that the Lévy walk generates heavy tails through a single mechanism (long ballistic flights), whereas the vortex tracer requires multiple strong vortex encounters to accumulate a large displacement, introducing a characteristic timescale for tail development.

---

## 6. Ergodicity Breaking

The ergodicity-breaking parameter EB(Δt) = Var(TAMSD(Δt)) / Mean(TAMSD(Δt))², computed from the per-trajectory time-averaged MSDs, is shown as a function of lag time on log-log axes in Fig. <code>fig6_ergodicity.png</code>. The EB parameter quantifies the degree to which individual tracer trajectories deviate from the ensemble average: EB = 0 corresponds to perfect ergodicity, while EB > 0 indicates that different trajectories sample different effective diffusivities.

The EB plateau values (mean over the last 20% of lag times) are:

| Configuration | EB plateau |
|---------------|------------|
| N = 5 | ~0.45 |
| N = 10 | ~0.32 |
| N = 20 | ~0.21 |
| N = 40 | ~0.18 |
| β = 1.2 | ~0.62 |
| β = 1.5 | ~0.48 |
| β = 1.8 | ~0.31 |
| β = 2.5 | ~0.12 |

Several important observations emerge from these results. First, the EB plateau decreases monotonically with increasing N for the vortex configurations, indicating that the system becomes more ergodic as the vortex field becomes more chaotic. This is the opposite trend to that observed in the Lévy walk dataset, where EB increases with decreasing β (stronger superdiffusion). This divergence in the EB-α relationship between the two systems is a key distinguishing feature that is further explored in the regime map (Section 7).

Second, the EB values for the vortex configurations are substantially elevated above zero even for N = 40, indicating significant non-ergodicity. However, it is important to note that with only 5 tracers per vortex configuration, the statistical uncertainty on the EB estimate is large: the standard error on the EB plateau is approximately ±0.08 for all vortex configurations, meaning that the differences between N = 20 and N = 40 are marginally significant. The Lévy walk EB estimates are
